g.title: n0
g.text: Devonian Strata as CAM
In Devon, all the strata - older than
the New Red Sandstone - are Cambrian
in age #GRE #H1

g.title: n1
g.text: Culm as CM
The Devonian Culm strata are Coal
Measures in age #COA #H2

g.title: n53
g.text: Unbroken Sequence - GRE.1a
If, in Devon, all the strata are
Cambrian in age, i.e. belonging to the
same geological period, then there is
no gap in the local sequence. #GRE

g.title: n20
g.text: Non-Culm Strata as CAM
In Devon, the non-Culm strata are
Cambrian in age #COA #chron-hyp

g.title: n26
g.text: Culm as ML and ORS
The Culm strata encompass the Old Red
Sandstone and the Mountain Limestone
#DEV #chron-hyp

g.title: n27
g.text: Culm as SIL
The whole Culm strata of Devonshire are
Silurian in age #GRE #chron-hyp

g.title: n63
g.text: Culm as CAM
If, in Devon, all the strata are
Cambrian in age, then the Culm strata
are Cambrian in age, too #GRE

g.title: n18
g.text: ORS in Devon
In Devon, a significant part of strata
is equivalent to the Old Red Sandstone
#DEV #chron-hyp

g.title: n54
g.text: Postulating A Major Gap - COA.1
If the Culm strata are Coal Measures in
age and juxtaposed with Cambrian
strata, then there is a major gap in
the local sequence #COA

g.title: n57
g.text: Postulating A Major Gap - COA.2a
If the Culm strata are Coal Measures in
age and juxtaposed with Silurian and
Cambrian strata, then there is a major
gap in the local sequence #COA

g.title: n61
g.text: Postulating A Minor Gap - COA.4
If the Culm strata - being at oldest
Coal Measures in age - are juxtaposed
with strata ranging from Silurian to
Old Red Sandstone, then there is a gap
in the local sequence #COA

g.title: n21
g.text: Black Culm Limestone as USIL
The Culm limestone belongs to the upper
part of the Silurian system. #COA
#chron-hyp

g.title: n22
g.text: Main part of the Culm as CM
In Devon, the main part of the Culm
strata is Coal Measures in age #COA
#chron-hyp

g.title: n23
g.text: Black Culm Limestone as USIL and ORS
The balck Culm limestone encompasses
the upper part of the Silurian and the
whole of the Old Red Sandstone. #COA
#chron-hyp

g.title: n30
g.text: Culm as CAM
The whole Culm strata of Devonshire is
Cambrian in age #GRE #chron-hyp

g.title: n64
g.text: Culm as CM
If strata can be identified by means of
their embedded fossils and the Culm
strata are not Coal Measures in age,
then the Culm strata do not contain
Coal Measures plants #COA

g.title: n81
g.text: Culm as Youngest Strata
If, the non-Culm strata are Cambrian in
age, then the Culm strata - being Coal
Measures in age - are the youngest
Devonian strata #COA

g.title: n2
g.text: Unbroken Sequence of Devon Strata
In Devon, all the strata - older than
the New Red Sandstone - form an
unbroken sequence of strata #ev #E1

g.title: n6
g.text: Unconformity in Devon
In Devon, there is a major unconformity
between the Culm and the juxtaposed
strata #ev #E5

g.title: n11
g.text: Unconformity in Devon II
In Devon, there is a major unconformity
between the main part of the Culm and
black Culm limestone #ev #E10

g.title: n3
g.text: CM Plants in Devon Culm
In Devon, the Culm strata contain Coal
Measures fossil plants #ev #E2

g.title: n4
g.text: Trough through Exmoor
There is a trough through Exmoor -
formed by a band of limestone running
out to the north coast at Ilfracombe
and south of Barnstaple #ev #E3

g.title: n10
g.text: Distinct Limestones at Ilfracombe and
Barnstaple
The limestone at Ilfracombe and the
limestone south of Barnstaple are
distinct #ev #E9

g.title: n5
g.text: Instances of Coal in Ancient Strata
In Munster and Pennsylvannia, there are
coal deposits in pre-Old Red Sandstone
strata #ev #E4

g.title: n8
g.text: Munster Coal as Carboniferous
In Munster, the limestone and coal
seams are pre-Carboniferous in age #ev

g.title: n7
g.text: CM Plants in Ancient French Strata
In the Bocage, the limestones are
pre-Old Red Sandstone in age and
contain some Coal Measures fossil
plants #ev #E6

g.title: n9
g.text: Culm trough in Central Devon
In central Devon, there is a Culm
trough #ev #E8

g.title: n12
g.text: Yorkshire similarities
The Black Culm limestone in Devon is
similar to the Yorkshire limestone -
both in fossils and rock type #ev #E11

g.title: n13
g.text: CM Plants in North Devon
In north Devon, the non-Culm strata
contain fossils similar to Coal
Measures plants #ev #E12

g.title: n14
g.text: ML Fauna in South Devon
In south Devon, non-Culm strata fossils
are as old as the base of the Mountain
Limestone #ev #E13

g.title: n17
g.text: Common Species
Two formations deposited at widely
separated periods have few if any
species in common #COA #pri

g.title: n44
g.text: CM Plants in Ancient Strata
In pre-Old Red Sandstone strata, there
are fossil plants similar to those of
the Coal Measures #GRE #pri

g.title: n52
g.text: Fossil Criterion and Common Species
If two formations deposited at widely
separated periods have more than only
a few species in common, then strata
cannot be identified by means of their
imbedded fossils #COA

g.title: n76
g.text: Culm and CM Plants
If the Devon Culm strata are pre-Old
Red Sandstone in age and there are no
Coal Measures plants in pre-Old Red
Sandstone strata, then there are no
Coal Measures plants in the Devon Culm
strata #GRE

g.title: n78
g.text: French Ancient Strata and CM Plants
If there are no Coal Measures plants in
pre-Old Red Sandstone strata, then
there were no Coal Measures plants in
French pre-Old Red Sandstone strata
#GRE

g.title: n45
g.text: Flora Similarities as Best Explanation
The best explanation of the existence
of coal in some strata G is the
similarity between G's flora and the
one of the Coal Measures (the Coal
Measures being noted for the great
amounts of coal they contain) #GRE

g.title: n77
g.text: Coal and CM Plants
If the similarity between the floras of
the Coal Measures and pre-Old Red
Sandstone formations is the best
explanation for the existence of coal
deposists in pre-Old Red Sandstone
strata, then there are Coal Measures
plants in pre-Old Red Sandstone
strata. #GRE

g.title: n46
g.text: Ancient French Strata
In the Bocage, there are pre-Old Red
Sandstone strata. #GRE #chron-hyp

g.title: n47
g.text: Lyellian Principals
At the earth's surface, there is a
constant but piecemeal change in the
composition of the faunas and floras
(in correlation with ever-changing
physical environments) #COA #pri

g.title: n79
g.text: Assemblages of Species
From Lyellian principals, it follows
that while particular species might
have long ranges in time, an
assemblage of many species does not
remain unchanged for long; therefore,
two formations deposited at widely
separated periods have few if any
species in common #COA

g.title: n19
g.text: Gap in a Sequence of Strata
There is a gap in a local sequence of
strata, iff there are strata
juxtaposed belonging to different but
not successive geological periods #GRE
#pri

g.title: n55
g.text: Postulating A Major Gap - COA.3.1
If the main part of the Culm strata are
Coal Measures and underlain by the
black Culm limestone which is at
youngest Silurian in age, then there
is a major gap in the local sequence
#COA

g.title: n56
g.text: Postulating A Minor Gap - COA.3.2
If the main part of the Culm strata are
Coal Measures and underlain by the
black Culm limestone which is at
youngest Old Red Sandstone in age,
then there is a gap in the local
sequence #COA

g.title: n58
g.text: Postulating A Minor Gap - COA.2b
If the Culm strata - at oldest Mountain
Limestone in age - are juxtaposed with
Cambrian and Silurian strata, then
there is a gap in the local sequence
#COA

g.title: n59
g.text: Devonian Interpretation - DEV.1
If the Culm strata - at oldest Old Red
Sandstone in age - are juxtaposed with
Silurian and Cambrian strata, then
there is no gap in the local sequence
#DEV

g.title: n60
g.text: Extending the Sequence Upwards - GRE.2
If the Culm strata - being Silurian in
age - are juxtaposed with strata
ranging from Cambrian to Silurian,
then there is no gap in the local
sequence #GRE

g.title: n62
g.text: Devonian Interpretation - DEV.2a
If the Culm strata - being at oldest
Mountain Limestone in age - are
juxtaposed with strata ranging from
Cambrian to Old Red Sandstone, then
there is no gap in the local sequence
#DEV

g.title: n28
g.text: Non-Culm Strata as SIL and ORS
In Devon, the non-Culm strata encompass
Silurian and Old Red Sandstone strata
#COA #chron-hyp

g.title: n37
g.text: SIL in North Devon
In north Devon (around Pilton), some
non-Culm strata are Silurian in age
#COA #chron-hyp

g.title: n38
g.text: Main part of non-Culm as CAM
In Devon, the main part of the non-Culm
strata is Cambrian in age #COA
#chron-hyp

g.title: n24
g.text: Non-Culm Strata as SIL and CAM
In Devon, the non-Culm strata range
from Cambrian to Silurian in age #COA
#chron-hyp

g.title: n41
g.text: Main part of non-Culm as CAM and SIL
In Devon, the main part of the non-Culm
strata range from Cambrian to Silurian
in age #DEV #chron-hyp

g.title: n29
g.text: Non-Culm Strata as CAM, SIL and ORS
In Devon, the non-Culm strata encompass
Cambrian, Silurian and Old Red
Sandstone strata #DEV #chron-hyp

g.title: n70
g.text: Extending the Sequence Onwards II -
COA.3a
If, in Devon, the main part of the
non-Culm strata is Cambrian and some
smaller part Silurian in age, then the
non-Culm strata encompass the Cambrian
and the Silurian #COA

g.title: n72
g.text: Extending the Sequence Onwards III -
COA.4
If, in Devon, the main part of the
non-Culm strata is Old Red Sandstone
and some smaller part Silurian in age,
then the non-Culm strata encompasses
the Cambrian and the Silurian #COA

g.title: n39
g.text: Main part of non-Culm as ORS
In north Devon, the main part of the
non-Culm strata are Old Red Sandstone
in age #COA #chron-hyp

g.title: n71
g.text: ORS Non-Culm Strata in North Devon
If strata can be identified by means of
their embedded fossil and some north
Devonian non-Culm strata are not Old
Red Sandstone in age, then there are
no Coal Measures plants in north
Devonian strata #COA

g.title: n40
g.text: Upper ORS in South Devon
In south Devon, some limestones are as
old as the base of the Mountain
Limestone #DEV #chron-hyp

g.title: n73
g.text: ORS Non-Culm Strata in South Devon
If strata can be identified by means of
their embedded fossil and some south
Devonian non-Culm strata are not as
old as the base of the Mountain
Limestone, then there are no Mountain
Limestone fossils in south Devonian
strata #DEV

g.title: n74
g.text: Extending the Sequence Onwards IV -
DEV.2a
If, in Devon, the main part of the
non-Culm strata range from Cambrian to
Silurian in age and some smaller part
is as old as the base of the Mountain
limestone, then the non-Culm strata
encompasses the Cambrian, Silurian and
the whole of the Old Red Sandstone #DEV

g.title: n31
g.text: Main part of Culm Limestone as USIL
In Devon, the main part of the black
Culm limestone is upper Silurian in
age #COA #chron-hyp

g.title: n35
g.text: Black Culm Limestone as ML
The Culm limestone is Mountain
Limestone in age #COA #chron-hyp

g.title: n36
g.text: Main part of the Culm as ML
In Devon, the main part of the Culm
strata is Mountain Limestone in age
#DEV #chron-hyp

g.title: n68
g.text: Extending the Sequence Downwards -
COA.2b
If, in Devon, the main part of the Culm
strata is Coal Measures and their
lower part Mountain Limestone in age,
then the Culm strata range from
Mountain Limestone to Coal Measures
#COA

g.title: n25
g.text: Culm as CM and ML
In Devon, the main or plant-bearing
part of the Culm strata is Coal
Measures in age, a lower part -
particularly the black Culm limestone
- is Mountain Limestone in age #COA
#chron-hyp

g.title: n65
g.text: Extending the Sequence Onwards - COA.3
If, in Devon, the main part of the
black Culm limestone is upper Silurian
and its upper part Old Red Sandstone
in age, then the balck Culm limestone
encompasses the upper part of the
Silurian and the whole of the Old Red
Sandstone #COA

g.title: n32
g.text: Part of Culm Limestone as ORS
Some part of the black Culm limestone
is Old Red Sandstone in age #COA
#chron-hyp

g.title: n69
g.text: Extending the Sequence Downwards II -
DEV.1
If, in Devon, the main part of the Culm
strata is Coal Measures and their
lower part Mountain Limestone in age,
then the Culm strata range from
Mountain Limestone to Coal Measures
#DEV

g.title: n33
g.text: Yorkshire Limestone as ML
In Yorkshire, the limestone is Mountain
Limestone in age #COA #chron-hyp

g.title: n67
g.text: Black Culm Limestone and Yorkshire II
If the black Culm limestone is as old
as the Yorkshire limestone being
Mountain Limestone in age, then the
Culm limestone is Mountain Limestone
in age, too #COA

g.title: n34
g.text: Yorkshire and Culm Limestone
The black Culm limestone is as old as
the Yorkshire limestone #COA #chron-hyp

g.title: n66
g.text: Black Culm Limestone and Yorkshire I
If strata can be identified by means of
their embedded fossils and the black
Culm limestone is not as old as the
Yorkshire limestone, then there are no
similarities in fossils between them
#COA

g.title: n42
g.text: Coal in Ancient Strata
There are coal deposits in pre-Old Red
Sandstone strata #GRE #pri

g.title: n75
g.text: Coal in Ancient Strata
If there are no coal deposits in
Pre-Old Red Sandstone strata, then
there are no coal deposits in the
pre-Old Red Sandstone strata of
Munster and Pennsylvannia #GRE

g.title: n43
g.text: Instances of Ancient Strata
In Munster and Pennsylvannia, there are
pre-Old Red Sandstone strata #GRE
#chron-hyp

g.title: n48
g.text: Formation of strata
Strata are originally formed from
sediments that were deposited in flat
horizontal sheets - the younger
sediments deposited on older ones.
#GRE #pri

g.title: n80
g.text: Trough through Exmoor - GRE.1a
If originally younger strata rest upon
older ones and the strata of Exmoor
are sandwiched between older strata,
then the strata of Exmoor are located
in a trough #GRE

g.title: n82
g.text: Culm trough - COA.2b
If originally younger strata rest upon
older ones and the Culm strata are
sandwiched between older strata, then
the Culm strata are located in a
trough #COA

g.title: n49
g.text: Definition Trough
Iff the strata are folded into an
archlike form, with the concave side
upward, then they form a trough #GRE
#pri

g.title: n50
g.text: Exmoor Youngest Devonian strata
In Devon, among all the strata older
than the New Red Sandstone, the strata
of Exmoor are the youngest #GRE
#chron-hyp

g.title: n51
g.text: Culm Youngest Devonian Strata
In Devon, among all the strata older
than the New Red Sandstone, the Culm
strata are the youngest #COA #chron-hyp

g.title: n15
g.text: Standard Sequence
Cambrian strata are overlain by
Silurian strata, Old Red Sandstone
strata, Mountain Limestone strata,
Coal Measures strata and New Red
Sandstone strata, respectively #COA
#pri

g.title: n16
g.text: Fossil Criterion
Strata can be identified by means of
their imbedded fossils #COA #pri
